name: Hartford Fire Insurance Company v. California
question: First, did the plaintiffs sufficiently allege "boycotts," as used in the McCarran-Ferguson Act, Section 3(b)? Second, did international comity counsel against exercising Sherman Act jurisdiction over the conduct of the London-based defendants?

name: Minnesota v. Dickerson
question: When a police officer detects contraband through his or her sense of touch during a protective patdown search, does the Fourth Amendment permit its seizure and subsequent introduction into evidence? Was the police officer who frisked Dickerson adhering to the Fourth Amendment when he formed the belief, through his sense of touch, that the lump in Dickerson's jacket pocket was cocaine?

name: Deal v. United States
question: Does a criminal's second through sixth convictions under section 924(c)(1) in a single proceeding arise "in the case of his second or subsequent conviction" within the meaning of section 924(c)(1)?

name: United States v. California
question: May the United States Government receive compensation for the state of California's allegedly unfounded taxation of a private federal contractor?

name: Hazen Paper Company v. Biggins
question:
Did the Courts below err in sustaining Biggin's claim under the ADEA, where the finding of age discrimination was based on pension vesting?

Did the Court of Appeals err in reinstating an award of liquidated damages for willful ADEA violation that had been set aside by the District Court?

name: Heller  v. Doe
question: Do Kentucky's involuntary commitment procedures for retarded persons violate the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment?

name: Godinez v. Moran
question: Does the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment require a trial court to apply a heightened "reasoned choice" standard to determine the competency of a defendant to enter a plea of guilty or waive counsel?

name: Zobrest v. Catalina Foothills School District
question: May a school district decline to provide an interpreter to a deaf child based on the Establishment Clause of the First Amendment?

name: Graham v. Collins
question: Would granting Graham the writ of habeas corpus create a new constitutional rule that would require special jury instructions on the consideration of the mitigating circumstances the defense presented?
description: A case in which the Court declined to create a new constitutional rule that would require special jury instructions to consider the mitigating circumstances of the defendant's youth and troubled family life.

name: United States v. Edge Broadcasting Company
Concrete Pipe and Products of California, Inc. v. Construction Laborers Pension Trust for Southern California
Republic Nat'l Bank of Miami v. United States
United States v. Parcel of Rumson, N. J., Land
Newark Morning Ledger Company v. United States
Withrow v. Williams
question: Does the Supreme Court's ruling in Stone v. Powell that federal habeas corpus review does not cover Fourth Amendment unreasonable search and seizure claims when defendants have already been given a fair chance to argue those claims in state court also apply to Fifth Amendment claims stemming from the withholding of Miranda warnings?

name: Shaw v. Reno
question: Did the North Carolina residents' claim, that the State created a racially gerrymandered district, raise a valid constitutional issue under the Fourteenth Amendment's Equal Protection Clause?
description: A case in which the Court held that the redistricting of North Carolina was evidence of an attempt to separate voters based on race, and thus raised a constitutional issue under the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment.

name: Church of Scientology of California v. United States
United States Department of Treasury v. Fabe
Moreau v. Klevenhagen
question: Can the Sheriff’s department take advantage of the compensatory time exception from the FLSA absent a collective bargaining agreement in a state that prohibits collective bargaining agreements, but employees have a union representative for other purposes?

name: Rowland v. California Men's Colony, Unit II Men's Advisory Council
Wisconsin v. Mitchell
question: Did the increase in Mitchell's sentence based on his bigoted motives violate his First Amendment rights?

name: Lamb's Chapel v. Center Moriches Union Free School District
question: Did the District violate the First Amendment's freedom of speech when it denied Lamb's Chapel the use of school premises to show religious-oriented films?

name: Building and Construction Trades Council of Metropolitan District v. Associated Builders and Contractors of Massachusetts/Rhode Island, Inc.
City of Cincinnati v. Discovery Network, Inc.
Commissioner of Internal Revenue v. Soliman
Herrera v. Collins
question: Was an individual sentenced to death for murder, Leonel Herrera, entitled to federal habeas corpus relief under the Eighth and Fourteenth Amendments when his petition was based on a claim of actual innocence without an accompanying federal constitutional violation?

name: Spectrum Sports, Inc. v. McQuillan
question: Is Spectrum liable for Sherman Act violations where the jury inferred intent and a dangerous possibility of success from Spectrum’s predatory conduct?

name: El Vocero de Puerto Rico v. Puerto Rico
Church of Lukumi Babalu Aye, Inc. v. City of Hialeah
question: Did the city of Hialeah's ordinance, prohibiting ritual animal sacrifices, violate the First Amendment's Free Exercise Clause?
description: A case in which the Court found that an ordinance banning religious animal sacrifice was unconstitutional under the Free Exercise Clause of the First Amendment.

name: Brecht v. Abrahamson
question: Is the "beyond a reasonable doubt" standard from Chapman v. California the appropriate standard for setting aside a conviction on the basis of constitutional error?

name: Granite State Insurance Company v. Tandy Corporation
Helling v. McKinney
question: May an inmate sue to prove that his Eighth Amendment right to be free from cruel and unusual punishment has been violated by prison officials who act with "deliberate indifference" to the future health risks associated with second-hand smoke?

name: St. Mary's Honor Center v. Hicks
Pioneer Investment Services Company v. Brunswick Associates Limited Partnership
Martin v. District of Columbia Court of Appeals
United States National Bank of Oregon v. Independent Insurance Agents of America, Inc.
Northeastern Florida Chapter, Associated General Contractors of America v. City of Jacksonville, Florida
question: In order to have standing to challenge the Jacksonville, Florida ordinance favoring minority-owned businesses, must an association of contractors demonstrate that at least one of its members would have received a city contract in the absence of the ordinance?

name: Professional Real Estate Investors, Inc. v. Columbia Pictures Industries, Inc.
Federal Communications Commission v. Beach Communications, Inc.
question: Is there a conceivable rational basis justifying the distinction between cable facilities that serve separately owned and managed buildings and those that serve one or more buildings under common ownership or management for purposes of the Due Process Clause of the Fifth Amendment?

name: Austin v. United States
question: Does the Excessive Fines Clause of the Eighth Amendment apply to a statutory in rem forfeiture of property?
description: A case in which the Court held that the Excessive Fines Clause of the Eighth Amendment applied to a statutory in rem forfeiture of property.

name: Cardinal Chemical Company v. Morton International, Inc.
question: Can a federal court, with exclusive jurisdiction over all federal appeals concerning patent litigation, use its finding that a patent has not been infringed as a per se justification for upholding the validity of the disputed patents themselves?

name: TXO Production Corporation v. Alliance Resources Corporation
Smith v. United States
question: Does trading a gun for drugs make a convicted defendant eligible for sentence enhancement under a federal law, which requires such treatment if the defendant "during and in relation to . . . [a] drug trafficking crime[,] uses . . . a firearm?"

name: Oklahoma Tax Commission v. Sac and Fox Nation
Harper v. Virginia Department of Taxation
Local 144 Nursing Home Pension Fund v. Demisay
Musick, Peeler & Garrett v. Employers Insurance of Wausau
Itel Containers International Corporation v. Huddleston
United States v. Dixon
question: Does the Double Jeopardy Clause bar prosecution of a defendant on substantive criminal charges based on the same conduct for which the defendant previously has been held in contempt of court?

name: Bath Iron Works Corp. v. Director, Office of Workers' Compensation Programs
Brooke Group Ltd. v. Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corporation
United States By and Through Internal Revenue Service v. McDermott
Reno v. Catholic Social Services, Inc.
Puerto Rico Aqueduct and Sewer Authority v. Metcalf & Eddy, Inc.
Leatherman v. Tarrant County Narcotics Intelligence and Coordination Unit
United States v. Louisiana (Alabama and Missippi Boundary Case)
Johnson v. Texas
question: Did the Texas capital sentencing statute unconstitutionally preclude the jury from fully considering the mitigating effect of the petitioner's youth at the time of the crime?

name: Sale v. Haitian Centers Council, Inc.
question: Is Executive Order No. 12807 a violation of section 243(h) or Article 33?

name: District of Columbia v. Greater Washington Bd. of Trade
Commissioner v. Keystone Consol. Industries, Inc.
Alexander v. United States
question:
1. Does property forfeiture under RICO as punishment for the distribution of obscene materials constitute 'prior restraint' on speech in violation of the First Amendment?

  2. Does the forfeiture of a business as punishment for the sale of obscene media constitute an 'excessive fine'?

name: Daubert v. Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, Inc.
Bufferd v. Commissioner of Internal Revenue
United States v. Idaho ex rel. Director, Idaho Dept. of Water Resources
Nixon v. United States
question: Is Nixon's claim -- that Senate Rule XI violates the Impeachment Trial Clause -- justiciable, i.e., appropriate for judicial resolution?
description: A case in which the Court held that Senate Rule XI was not subject to judicial review because the "Senate shall have sole Power to try any impeachments."
